The '''Nissan Leaf''' (also formatted "LEAF" as a [[bacronym]] for ''Leading, Environmentally friendly, Affordable, Family car''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.yahoo.com/s/afp/20101214/bs_afp/usjapanautocompanynissanenvironment|title=Nissan delivers first Leaf in San Francisco|work=Yahoo News|date=2010-12-13|accessdate=2020-12-21}}</ref>) is a five-door [[mid-size car|mid-size]] [[hatchback]] [[electric car]] manufactured by [[Nissan]] and introduced in Japan and the U.S. in December 2010.<ref name=LaunchUS/><ref name=LaunchJap>{{cite news|url=http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=131771329|title=Nissan Rolls Out Leaf Electric Car In Japan|agency=Associated Press|date=2010-12-03|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref><ref name=Launch1220>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/12/nissan-leaf-officially-on-sale-in-us-dec-11-japan-launch-set-for-dec-20.html|title=Nissan Leaf Officially On Sale in U.S. Dec. 11; Japan Launch Set for Dec. 20|publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|author=John O'Dell|date=2010-12-03|accessdate=2010-12-03}}</ref> The Leaf is the first mass-produced electric car for sale from a major manufacturer.<ref name=Launch3>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideline.com/nissan/leaf/2011/first-production-nissan-leaf-electric-vehicle-delivered-to-customer.html|title=First Production Nissan Leaf Electric Vehicle Delivered to Customer|publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|author=Scott Doggett|date=2010-12-11|accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref> The [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] determined the range to be {{Convert|73|mi|disp=flip}}, with an energy consumption of 765 [[kilojoule|kJ]]/km (34 [[kWh]] per 100 miles) and rated the Leaf's combined [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] at 99 [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent]].<ref name=NYTEPA>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/23/business/23leaf.html?_r=1&hpw|title=Nissan Says Its Electric Leaf Gets Equivalent of 99 M.P.G.|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Nick Bunkley|date=2010-11-22|accessdate=2010-11-23}}</ref><ref name=GCCEPA/>

Deliveries began in the United States on December 11, 2010,<ref name=LaunchUS/> and on December 22 in Japan.<ref name=JapanDeliver1>{{cite news|url=http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2010/12/22/nissan-delivers-first-leaf-in-japan/|title=Nissan delivers first Leaf in Japan|publisher=The Green Car Website|date=2020-12-22|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref> Sales are scheduled to begin in Portugal in January 2011, Ireland in February, the United Kingdom in March, and the Netherlands in June, with global market availability planned for 2012.<ref name=Nissan073010/><ref name=Global2012>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSLDE62G2MB20100318|title=Nissan to build Leaf electric car in UK from 2013|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=2010-03-17|accessdate=2010-12-31}}</ref> Nissan announced that initial availability is limited in quantities and to select markets and only for customers who made online reservations. The availability will be increased by the second quarter of 2011 with U.S. production planned for 2012.<ref name=Leaf0420>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/feature/pricing_information#/leaf-electric-car/feature/pricing_information|title=Nissan LEAF Pricing information|publisher=Nissan|accessdate=2010-04-20}}</ref><ref name=NYT0420>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/04/20/nissan-to-begin-firming-up-leaf-reservation-list/|title=Nissan to Begin Firming Up Leaf Reservation List|work=The New York Times|author=Jim Motavalli|date=2010-04-20|date=2010-04-0|accessdate=2010-04-19}}</ref><ref name=GCC0410/>

The Leaf's retail price in Japan starts at {{yen|3.76}} million and {{USD|32,780}} in the United States. The price announced in the United Kingdom is {{GBP|28,350}} and around {{<U+20AC>|35,000}} in the other three European countries where it will be launched first. These prices include the price of the battery package.  Most countries have applicable [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles|tax incentives or subsidies]] for eligible buyers that reduce the effective cost of purchase below the retail prices listed by Nissan.<ref name=Nissan073010/><ref name=GCC0330>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/03/leaf-imiev-20100330.html#more|title=Nissan Prices LEAF in Japan Starting at <U+00A5>3.76M (US$40.5K); Mitsubishi Begins Sales of i-MiEV to Individuals at <U+00A5>3.98M |publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-03-30|accessdate=2010-03-30}}</ref><ref name=PriceUS>{{cite web|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/36092225/ns/business-autos/|title=With credits, Nissan electric could cost $25K|publisher=Autos on msnbc.com|author=Malcolm Foster|date=2010-03-30|accessdate=2010-12-04}}</ref><ref name=ABGreen0510>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/05/17/nissan-announces-european-prices-for-leaf-under-30-000-after-i/|title=Nissan announces European prices for Leaf, under <U+20AC>30,000 after incentives|author=Sam Abuelsamid|date=2010-05-17|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref>

As an [[all-electric car]] the Nissan Leaf produces no [[motor vehicle emissions|tailpipe pollution]] or [[greenhouse gas emissions]] at the point of operation, and reduces dependence on [[petroleum]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.economist.com/node/17202405?story_id=17202405|title=Electric cars: A sparky new motor |work=The Economist|date=2010-10-07|accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/08/business/08electric.html?ref=electricvehicles|title=First Buyers of Nissan Leaf Get a Trunkful of Perks |work=The New York Times|date=2010-10-07|accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref> Among other awards and recognition, the Nissan Leaf won the 2010 [[Green Car Vision Award]] award<ref name=GreenAward/> and the 2011 [[European Car of the Year]] award.<ref name=ECOTY/>

== History of development ==
{{Multiple image | direction = horizontal | align = right
| image1 = Nissan EV-01 200811.JPG
| width1 = 180
| caption1 = The [[Nissan Cube]]-derived EV-01 test car was Nissan's first [[prototype]] with the [[battery electric vehicle|all-electric drive train]] later used in the Leaf.

| image2 = EV-12 test car (Nissan Leaf).jpg
| width2 = 270
| caption2 = The EV-12 test car was based on the [[Nissan Tiida|Nissan Tiida/Versa]].
}}

Nissan introduced its first [[battery electric vehicle]], the [[Nissan Altra]] at the [[Los Angeles International Auto Show]] on 29 December 1997.<ref name=AltraPR>{{cite web|url=http://www.theautochannel.com/news/press/date/19971229/press008845.html|title=All-New Nissan Altra EV: A Friendly, High-Tech Electric Vehicle for Everyday Life|publisher=The Auto Channel|date=1997-12-29|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref> The Altra EV was produced between 1998 and 2002, only about 200 vehicles were ever produced, and it was mainly used as a [[fleet vehicle]] for companies such as electric utilities.<ref name=gutenberg>{{cite web|url=http://jcwinnie.biz/wordpress/?p=1702|title=Nissan Altra Electric Retrieved from Vacaville|publisher=After Gutenberg|date=2006-07-02|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref><ref name=EVworld>{{cite web|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20071117214154/http://www.evworld.com/archives/testdrives/altra.html|title=California Commuter|publisher=EV World|accessdate=2010-12-23|date=2001-01-31 |archiveurl =http://web.archive.org/web/20071117214154/http://www.evworld.com/archives/testdrives/altra.html|archivedate = 2007-11-17}}</ref>

Unveiled in 2009, the EV-11 [[prototype]] [[electric car]] was based on the [[Nissan Tiida]] (Versa in North America), but with the conventional gasoline engine replaced with an [[battery electric vehicle|all-electric drivetrain]], including an {{convert|80|kW|hp|abbr=on}}/{{convert|280|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} [[electric motor]], 24&nbsp;kW<U+00B7>h [[lithium-ion battery]] pack rated to have a range of {{convert|109|mi|km|disp=flip}} on the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]]'s LA-4 or "city" [[driving cycle]], [[automotive navigation system|navigation system]], and [[remote diagnostics|remote control and monitoring]] using a [[mobile phone|cellphone]] connection through Nissan's secure [[data center]] to the car.<ref name=EV11/> The technology in the EV-11 was previously developed and tested in the EV-01 and EV-02 test cars, built with an all-electric [[powertrain]] using the [[Nissan Cube]] (Z11) as a [[development mule]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/26051059/|title=Nissan shows test models of electric car, hybrid|publisher=MSNBC News|agency=Associated Press|date=2008-08-06|accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-13746_7-10210982-48.html|title=Test-driving the Nissan EV-02 electric car|publisher=cnet|author=Antuan Goodwin|date=2009-04-02|accessdate=2010-04-25}}</ref> The EV-11 prototype was on display July 26, 2009.<ref name=EV11>{{cite web|last=Abuelsamid |first=Sam |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/07/27/nissan-shows-off-new-versa-based-electric-vehicle-prototype/ |title=Nissan shows off new Versa-based electric vehicle prototype |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=2009-07-27 |accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref> A week later, on August 2, 2009, Nissan unveiled its production version at its Yokohama headquarters and is set to begin selling in both the North American market and Japan at end of 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paukert |first=Chris |url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/08/01/2010-nissan-leaf-electric-car-in-person-in-depth-and-u-s-b/ |title=2010 Nissan Leaf electric car: In person, in depth <U+2013> and U.S. bound |publisher=Autoblog.com |date=2009-08-01 |accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref><ref name="nissan unveils PR">{{cite press release |title=Nissan unveils "LEAF" - the world's first electric car designed for affordability and real-world requirements |url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2009/_STORY/090802-02-e.html |publisher=Nissan |date=2009-08-02 |accessdate=2010-05-13}}</ref>

===Design===
{{Multiple image | direction = vertical | align = right | width = 200
| image1 = Nissan Leaf 013.JPG
| caption1 = Leaf interior

| image2 = NISSAN LEAF motor room.jpg
| caption2 = Leaf electric motor

| image3 = Nissan Leaf 012.JPG
| caption3 = Leaf [[lithium-ion battery]] pack
}}

The Leaf's frontal styling is characterized by a sharp V-shape design with large, up slanting light-emitting diode (LED) headlights that create a distinctive blue internal reflective design. The headlights also split and redirect airflow away from the door mirrors, reducing wind noise and drag. The headlights consume 50% less electricity than halogen lamps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVwtwhvmK0I |title=Nissan Leaf electric vehicle <U+2013> MPG-o-Matic! 7m20s |author=YouTube |date=2010-01-31 |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=2010-05-28}}</ref> Nissan sought not to deter individuals away from the Leaf, giving it a familiar sedan- and hatchback-like design.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allcarselectric.com/blog/1033843_2011-nissan-leaf-design-aimed-at-mainstream-appeal|title=2011 Nissan LEAF: Design Aimed at Mainstream Appeal|author=Eric Loveday |publisher=AllCarsElectric|date=2010-08-03|accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref> The bottom of the car has aerodynamic paneling to reduce drag and improve aerodynamics as much as possible.<ref>{{cite news|url=
http://www.motortrend.com/roadtests/alternative/1007_2011_nissan_leaf_vs_2012_mitsubishi_i_miev/exterior.html |title=Quick Comparison: 2011 Nissan Leaf vs. 2012 Mitsubishi i-MiEV |date=2010-08-03 |work=[[Motor Trend]]|accessdate=2010-08-03}}</ref>

===Powertrain===
Nissan says that the car has a top speed of over {{convert|150|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. Its motor is rated at {{convert|80|kW|hp}} and {{convert|280|N<U+00B7>m|lb<U+00B7>ft}}.<ref name='SAE Leaf'>{{cite web |author=Paul Weissler |url=http://www.sae.org/mags/aei/7714 |work=Automotive Engineering International Online |publisher=[[SAE International]] | title=Leaf to be sold with battery pack at C-segment price |date=2010-03-12 |accessdate=2010-04-13}}</ref> Unofficially, [[0 to 60 mph]] (0 to 97&nbsp;km/h) performance has been tested at 9.9&nbsp;seconds.<ref name=EdmundsTest/>

The Leaf uses a front-mounted [[electric motor]] driving the wheels, powered by a {{convert|24|kW<U+00B7>h|disp=flip}} [[lithium ion battery]] pack rated to deliver up to {{convert|90|kW|hp}} power.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-zeroemission.com/EN/LEAF/specs.html |title=Nissan Zero Emission Website &#124; Nissan LEAF &#124; Specs |publisher=Nissan-zeroemission.com |date= |accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref>  The pack contains air-cooled, stacked laminar battery cells with lithium manganate cathodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/05/27/details-on-nissan-leaf-battery-pack-including-how-recharging-sp/|title=Details on Nissan Leaf battery pack, including how recharging speed affects battery life |publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|date=2010-05-27|accessdate=2010-05-27}}</ref><ref name=HybridC0510>{{cite web|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/news/13-key-questions-and-answers-about-nissan-leaf-battery-pack-and-ordering-28007.html|publisher=HybridCars.com|date=2010-05-27|title=13 Key Questions and Answers about Nissan Leaf Battery Pack and Ordering|accessdate=2010-05-31}}</ref> The battery and control module together weigh {{convert|300|kg|lb}} and the [[specific energy]] of the cells is 140&nbsp;W<U+00B7>h/kg.<ref name='SAE Leaf' /> It is estimated that each battery pack costs Nissan {{USD|18,000}} ({{as of|2010|05|lc=on}}), and this cost is expected to be halved by mass production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/05/15/nissan-leaf-profitable-by-year-three-battery-cost-closer-to-18/|title=Nissan Leaf profitable by year three; battery cost closer to $18,000|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|date=2010-05-15|accessdate=2010-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://earth2tech.com/2010/05/17/nissan-leaf-like-other-electric-cars-will-lose-money-at-first/|publisher=Earth2tech|date=2010-05-17|title=Nissan: LEAF, Like Other Electric Cars, Will Lose Money at First |accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> Under its five-cycle testing, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] found the Leaf's energy consumption to be 765&nbsp;[[kilojoule|kJ]]/km (34&nbsp;[[kWh]]/100 miles) and rated the Leaf combined [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent|equivalent]] at 99&nbsp;MPGe (2.4&nbsp;L/100&nbsp;km), with an equivalent {{Convert|106|mpg|abbr=on}} in city driving and {{Convert|92|mpg|abbr=on}} on highways.<ref name=NYTEPA/><ref name=GCCEPA/>

The battery pack is expected to retain 70% to 80% of its capacity after 10 years but its actual lifespan depends on how often fast charging (440-volt) is used and also on environmental factors.<ref name=HybridC0510/>  Nissan stated the battery has a "lifespan of 5<U+2013>10 years under normal use".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/faq/list/technology|publisher=Nissan USA|title=Nissan Leaf Technology FAQ|quote=Q: How many charging cycles can the energy storage device survive? A: The battery will have a lifespan of 5<U+2013>10 years under normal use. We are still working to define all variables which will impact battery performance|accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref> In July 2010, Nissan announced that the Leaf's battery is guaranteed for eight years or {{convert|100000|mi|km}}.<ref name=GCC072710>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/07/nissan-to-warranty-leaf-battery-for-8-years-100000-miles-.html#more|title=Nissan to Warranty LEAF Battery for 8 Years, 100,000 Miles|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-27}}</ref><ref name=CNN072710>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2010/07/27/autos/volt_price/index.htm?hpt=T2|title=Chevy Volt priced at $41,000|author= Peter Valdes-Dapena|publisher=CNN Money|date2010-07-27|accessdate=2010-07-27 | date=2010-07-27}}</ref> The battery pack consists of 48 modules with each module containing 4 cells and is assembled by Automotive Energy Supply Corporation (AESC) <U+2013> a joint venture between Nissan, [[NEC]] and NEC Energy Devices.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/galleries/2010/fortune/1002/gallery.nissan_leaf.fortune/index.html|title=Nissan's Leaf up close |author=CNN |date=2010-02-17 |accessdate=2010-05-28}}</ref><ref name=Production1010>{{cite web |url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2010/_STORY/101022-01-e.html|title=Production of 100% Electric, Zero-Emission Nissan LEAF begins at Oppama, Japan|date=2010-10-22|publisher=Nissan News|accessdate=2011-01-06}}</ref> Since the battery is the heaviest part of any EV, Nissan housed the battery pack below the rear-seat compartment to keep the center of gravity as low as possible and also results in increased structural rigidity as compared to a conventional five-door hatchback.<ref name=EdmundsTest>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmunds.com/nissan/leaf/2011/road-test2.html|title=2011 Nissan Leaf Road Test|publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|accessdate=2011-01-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insideline.com/nissan/leaf/2011/2011-nissan-leaf-prototype-japan-first-drive.html|publisher=Edmunds Inside Line|title=2011 Nissan Leaf Prototype (Japan) First Drive|author=Peter Nunn|date=2010-06-23|accessdate=2011-01-01}}</ref>

===Recharging===
The Leaf has two charging receptacles: a standard [[SAE J1772]]-2009 connector for [[Level 1, 2, and 3 charging|level 1 and 2 recharging]] (120/220&nbsp;volts [[alternating current|AC]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/04/09/nissan-and-aerovironment-show-off-prototype-leaf-home-charger/ |title=Nissan and AeroVironment show off prototype $2,200 Leaf home charger |author=Eric Loveday |date=2010-04-09 |publisher=[[Autoblog Green]] |accessdate=2010-04-13}}</ref> and a JARI Level 3 DC connector designed by [[TEPCO]] for high-voltage, "[[Level 1, 2, and 3 charging|level 3]]" quick charging (480&nbsp;volts [[direct current|DC]] 125&nbsp;amps)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/01/akerwade-20100115.html |title=Tokyo Electric Power Licenses Aker Wade to Build Level III Fast Chargers |date=2010-01-15 |publisher=[[Green Car Congress]] |accessdate=2010-04-13}}</ref>
using the [[CHAdeMO]] protocol.<ref name="cars21 aker">{{cite web |url=http://www.cars21.com/content/articles/2010-04-29-exclusive-interview-with-bret-aker--standardisation-is-the-key.php |title=Exclusive interview with the CEO of Aker Wade: <U+201C>Standardisation is the key<U+201D> |date=2010-04-29 |publisher=cars21.com |accessdate=2010-05-13}}</ref>

{{Multiple image | direction = horizontal | align = left
| image1 = Nissan LEAF Charge Port.jpg
| width1 = 150

| image2 = Nissan Leaf dual charging outlets.jpg
| width2 = 170
| footer = The Leaf's charging port with two inlets is located in the front of the car.
}}

Using the on-board {{convert|3.3|kW|hp|adj=on}} charger<ref>{{cite web|last=Nissan|title=Nissan LEAF Electric Car {{!}} The New Car | Features and Specifications|url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/tags/show/range#/leaf-electric-car/specs-features/index|accessdate=18 August 2010}}</ref> and {{convert|7.5|m|adj=on|sp=us}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gas2.org/2010/05/27/nissan-leaf-will-include-fast-charge-capability-and-emergency-charging-cable-at-launch/ |title=Nissan LEAF Will Include Fast Charge Capability and Emergency Charging Cable at Launch |author=Nick Chambers |date=2010-05-27 |publisher=[http://gas2.org/ gas2.0] |accessdate=2010-06-13}}</ref> cable included by Nissan, the Leaf can be fully recharged from empty in under 20 hours from a [[Mains electricity|standard household outlet]] (120-volt, 15&nbsp;amp breaker, 12&nbsp;amp maximum allowable draw,<ref name="NEC Code for EVs" /> {{convert|1.4|kW|hp}}) in North America and Japan; recharging a partially discharged pack requires less time.<ref name="nissan-faq-charging">{{cite web |url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/faq/list/charging#/leaf-electric-car/faq/list/charging |title=Nissan LEAF Electric Car &#124; Answers &#124; Charging |publisher=Nissan |accessdate=2010-05-25}}</ref> It can be charged in 8 hours from a 220/240-volt 30&nbsp;amp supply ({{convert|5.2|kW|hp}} allowable draw<ref name="NEC Code for EVs" />) that can provide the on-board charger its full {{convert|3.3|kW|hp}} of usable power.<ref name="nissan-faq-charging" /><ref name='Nissan EV plans'>{{cite web |author=Christopher Sawyer |url=http://www.autofieldguide.com/articles/020903.html |publisher=Automotive Design and Production| title=Nissan's EV and Battery Plans |month=February | year=2009 |accessdate=2009-10-10}}</ref> U.S. electrical regulations require a 240-volt [[charging station]] to be permanently wired to an AC outlet unless proper interlock mechanisms are available to ensure the charging current can be safely turned on and off.<ref name="NEC Code for EVs">{{cite web |url=http://www.madkatz.com/ev/nec1999Article625.html |title=NEC 1999 National Electrical Code Article 625 <U+2013> Electric Vehicle Charging System |year=1999 |publisher=[[National Electrical Code]] |accessdate=2010-06-27 |quote=C. Equipment Construction

625<U+2013>13. Electric Vehicle Supply Equipment. Electric vehicle supply equipment rated at 125 volt, single phase, 15 or 20 amperes or part of a system identified and listed as suitable for the purpose and meeting the requirements of Sections 625<U+2013>18. 625<U+2013>19. and 625<U+2013>29 shall be permitted to be cord and plug connected. All other electric vehicle supply equipment shall be permanently connected and fastened in place. This equipment shall have no exposed live parts.}}</ref>  Nissan selected [[AeroVironment]] to supply its charging dock and installation services in North America,<ref>{{cite press release |title=Nissan North America Selects AeroVironment To Install Home-Charging Stations For Nissan Leaf |url=http://www.avinc.com/resources/press_release/nissan_north_america_selects_aerovironment_to_install_home-charging_station |publisher=AeroVironment |date=2010-01-11 |accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref>
(see the [[#United States|United States]] section below for more details).

Using level 3 quick charging, the battery pack can be charged to 80% capacity in about 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wired.com/autopia/2009/08/nissan-electric-leaf/ |title=Nissan Turns Over An Electric Leaf |author=Chuck Squatriglia |date=2009-09-02 |work=Autopia |publisher=''[[Wired News]]'' |accessdate=2010-05-13}}</ref>
Nissan developed its own 500-volt quick charger that went on sale in Japan for {{yen|1,470,000}} (around {{USD|16,800}}) in May 2010 and plans to install 200 at dealers in Japan.<ref name=QuickCharger>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2010/_STORY/100521-01-e.html |title=Nissan Introduces Quick EV Charger |publisher=Nissan Global Website |date=2010-05-21 |accessdate=2010-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/05/21/nissan-announces-49-kw-quick-charger-for-evs/2#c28103204|title=Nissan announces 49 kW quick charger for EVs | author=Sam Abuelsamid |date=2010-05-21 |publisher=[[Autoblog Green]] |accessdate=2010-05-25}}</ref> Nissan warns that if fast charging is the primary way of recharging, then the normal and gradual battery capacity loss is about 10% more than regular 220-volt charging over a 10-year period.<ref name=HybridC0510/> Other companies make compatible charging stations, and companies and local government have various initiatives to create networks of public charging stations<ref name="nissan-faq-charging" /><ref name="eetimes r-n-edf">{{cite web |url=http://www.automotive-eetimes.com/en/renault-nissan-_edf_to_develop_e-cars_and_infrastructure_in_france?cmp_id=7&news_id=211100106 |title=Renault-Nissan, EDF to develop e-cars and infrastructure in France |date=2008-10-10 | work=EE Times Europe automotive |publisher=[[EETimes]]|accessdate=2010-05-21}}</ref> (see [[electric vehicle network]]).

===Technology===
[[File:Nissan LEAF SL Solar Spoiler.jpg|thumb|Nissan Leaf SV spoiler-mounted solar panel]]

The Nissan Leaf employs an advanced [[telematics]] system called "Carwings" which originally was only available in Japan.<ref name=Carwings1>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/12/23/nissan-leaf-carwings-efficiency/|title=Nissan Leaf's CARWINGS keeps you up to speed, puts you in efficiency race|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|author=Domenick Yoney|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2008/01/28/nissan-carwings-telematics-system-gets-environmental-award-in-ja/|title=Nissan Carwings telematics system gets environmental award in Japan|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|author=Sam Abuelsamid|date=2008-01-28|accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref> The system sends and receives data via a built-in [[GPRS]] radio similar to the connectivity of mobile phones.  Carwings is connected any time the car is in range of a cell tower and it makes possible several user functionalities, such as position and possible range on a map and which charging stations are available within range. The system also tracks and compiles statistics about distance traveled and energy consumption and produces daily, monthly and annual reports of these and several other operating parameters. All information is available in the Leaf's digital screens.<ref name=Carwings1/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/nissan-launches-carwings-connected-system-for-leaf-with-remote-control-and-rankings/|title=Nissan Launches CARWINGS Connected System for Leaf with Remote Control and Eco Rankings|work=[[Car and Driver]]|author=Michael Austin|date=2011-01-05|accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref>  Users' mobile phones can be used to turn on the air-conditioner and heater, and reset charging functions even when the vehicle is powered down. This can be used to pre-heat or pre-cool the car prior to use. The advantage of doing this while still connected is so it does not discharge the battery and sets the climate before use. An on-board remote-controlled timer can also be pre-programmed to recharge batteries at a set time such as during off-peak rates.<ref name=LeafInfoSys>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/07/22/chelsea-sexton-nissan-leaf-uses-information-as-gateway-drug/|title=Nissan Leaf uses information as gateway drug|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|author=[[Chelsea Sexton]]|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-10-25}}</ref> The Leaf's SL trim has a small solar panel at the rear of the roof/spoiler that can trickle charge the auxiliary battery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cnettv.cnet.com/2011-nissan-leaf/9742-1_53-50080194.html|title=2011 Nissan Leaf - CNET |publisher=[[CNET]] CNET Car Tech|author=Brian Cooley|accessdate=2011-01-09}}</ref>
[[File:Nissan leaf paris test drive.ogv|thumb|left|Demonstration of the Leaf's electric motor quietness]]

Due to significant noise reduction typical of [[electric vehicle]]s traveling at low speeds, the Leaf includes [[Electric vehicle warning sounds|warning sounds]] <U+2013> one for forward motion and another for reverse for the alerting of pedestrians, the blind, and others to its presence.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/01/electric-car-warning-sounds-dont-expect-ringtones/|title=Electric Car Warning Sounds: Don<U+2019>t Expect Ring Tones|work=The New York Times|author=Jim Motavalli|date=2010-06-01|accessdate=2010-06-02}}</ref><ref name=NYT0610>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/06/17/blind-advocates-disappointed-in-nissan-e-v-sounds-for-pedestrians/?ref=automobiles|title=Blind Advocates <U+2018>Disappointed<U+2019> in Nissan E.V. Sounds for Pedestrians|work=The New York Times|author=Jim Motavalli|date=2010-06-17|accessdate=2010-06-19}} ''The article includes a sample of the two sounds''.</ref> For this purpose Nissan created the [[Vehicle Sound for Pedestrians]] (VSP) system, which also will be used in the upcoming [[Infiniti M#Hybrid version (2011<U+2013>)|Nissan Fuga hybrid]], due in 2011. The system developed makes a noise easy to hear for those outside in order to be aware of the vehicle approaching, but the warning sounds do not distract the car occupants inside. Nissan explained that during the development of the sound, they studied behavioral research of the visually impaired and worked with cognitive and acoustic psychologists.<ref name=NYT0610/><ref name=NissanNoise>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2010/_STORY/100611-01-e.html|title=Nissan demonstrates the affordable, 100% electric, zero-emission Nissan LEAF|publisher=[[Nissan]]|date=2010-06-11|accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref><ref name=AutoBlogNoise>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/06/14/nissan-leaf-will-break-the-ev-silence-with-a-digital-whistle-w/#continued|title=Nissan Leaf will break the EV silence with a digital whistle [w/video]|publisher=[[Autoblog]]|date=2010-06-14|accessdate=2010-06-15}} ''The article has a video with the Leaf warning sounds.''</ref> The sine-wave sound system sweeps from 2.5&nbsp;kHz at the high end to a low of 600&nbsp;Hz, an easily audible range across age groups. Depending on the speed and if the Leaf is accelerating or decelerating, the sound system makes sweeping, high-low sounds. The sound system ceases operation when the Nissan Leaf reaches {{convert|30|km/h|0}} and engages again as car slows to under {{convert|25|km/h|0}}. The driver can turn off sounds temporarily through a switch inside the vehicle, but the system automatically resets to "On" at the next ignition cycle. The system is controlled through a computer and synthesizer in the dash panel, and the sound is delivered through a speaker in the front driver<U+2019>s side [[wheel well]].<ref name=NYT0610/><ref name=NissanNoise/><ref name=JustAutoLeaf>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-auto.com/news/nissan-makes-leaf-noisier-at-low-speed_id104731.aspx?lk=dm|title=JAPAN: Nissan makes Leaf noisier at low speed|publisher=Just Auto|date=2010-06-11|accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref> After the new sounds were publicized, the [[National Federation of the Blind (United States)|US National Federation of the Blind]] issued a statement saying that "while it was pleased that the alert existed, it was unhappy that the driver was able to turn it off."<ref name=NYT0610/>

==Production==
[[File:Nissan Leaf.jpg|thumb|Nissan Leaf production model]]
The [[US Department of Energy]] initially granted {{USD|99.8 million}}, and later awarded an additional {{USD|15 million}}, to [[Electric Transportation Engineering Corporation|Electric Transportation Engineering Corporation (eTec)]] for the EV Project, involving the installation of up to 11,210 charging stations in strategic markets in [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] and [[Tucson, Arizona]]; [[San Diego, California]]; [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], [[Eugene, Oregon|Eugene]], [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] and [[Corvallis, Oregon]], [[Seattle, Washington]]; [[Nashville]], [[Knoxville]], and [[Chattanooga, Tennessee|Chattanooga]]; [[Washington D.C.]]; [[Dallas]], [[Fort Worth, Texas|Fort Worth]], and [[Houston, Texas]]. Nissan has partnered with eTec on this project and will supply 4,700 vehicles to individual and fleet customers in these areas.<ref name=eTec>{{cite web|url=http://www.theevproject.com/overview.php|title=The EV Project home website: list of participating cities (2010 deployment)|publisher=EV Project|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref><ref name=EdmundsEV>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2009/10/etec-signs-998-million-doe-contract-provides-scope-of-work-launches-website.html|title=eTec Signs $99.8 Million DOE Contract, Provides Scope of Work, Launches Website|publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|date=2009-10-01|author=Scott Doggett|accessdate=2010-04-27}}</ref>

The EV Project will collect and analyze data regarding vehicle use under different geographic and climatic conditions, for both commercial and public installations. The effectiveness of the deployed charge infrastructure will also be evaluated as part of the project with the goal of applying the lessons learned in order to improve the deployment of the full production number of Leafs and other EVs.<ref name=eTec/><ref name=EdmundsEV/>

The first vehicles sold in the US were produced at Nissan<U+2019>s plant in [[Oppama]], Japan, which started production on October 22, 2010.<ref name=Production1010/><ref name=NYT022009/> Commercial US production would begin in late 2012 at Nissan's manufacturing facility in [[Smyrna, Tennessee]]. This US plant will be modified with a {{USD|1.4 billion}} loan granted by the US Department of Energy to allow the manufacturing plant to produce the Nissan Leaf and its advanced batteries. The retooled plant is expected to create 1,300 jobs.<ref name=Electric/><ref name=USDoE>{{cite web|url=http://www.energy.gov/news/8581.htm|title=Secretary Chu Announces Closing of $1.4 Billion Loan to Nissan |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Energy]]|date=2010-01-28|accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref> The Smyrna plant is expected to produce up to 150,000 vehicles and 200,000 battery packs annually.<ref name=USDoE/>

The Leaf will also be produced at Nissan's plant in [[City of Sunderland|Sunderland]], England, beginning in 2013.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/8573724.stm|title=Nissan Leaf electric car to be built in Sunderland|publisher=BBC News|date=2010-03-18|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> Nissan will benefit from a <U+00A3>20.7m grant from the British government and up to <U+00A3>220m from the [[European Investment Bank]].<ref name=BBC/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allcarselectric.com/blog/1043590_third-factory-for-2011-nissan-leaf-production-is-smart-move-in-ev-production-war|title=Third Factory For 2011 Nissan Leaf Production Is Smart Move In EV Production War|publisher=AllCarsElectric.com|date=2010-03-19|accessdate=2010-03-19}}</ref> The plant will produce 60,000 lithium-ion batteries a year, and it also is expected to deliver 50,000 Leaf EVs a year.<ref name=BBC/>

==Market==
Nissan officially introduced the Leaf in a ceremony held at its global headquarters in [[Yokohama]] on December 3, 2010.<ref name=LaunchJap/> The first U.S. customer delivery took place in [[Northern California]] on December 11, 2010<ref name=LaunchUS>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/nissan-makes-history-with-delivery-of-worlds-first-100-electric-nissan-leaf-to-california-consumer-111725479.html?utm_source=twitterfeed&utm_medium=twitter|title=Nissan Makes History With Delivery of World's First 100% Electric Nissan LEAF to California Consumer|agency=PR Newswire|author=[[Nissan]]|date=2010-12-11|accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref> and the first delivery in Japan took place at the [[Kanagawa Prefecture]] on December 22.<ref name=JapanDeliver1/> Retail sales to individual consumers in Portugal, Ireland, the United Kingdom, and the Netherlands are scheduled to begin during the first quarter of 2011, and global market availability is planned for 2012.<ref name=Nissan073010/><ref name=Global2012/>

The Leaf does not have the [[Renault-Nissan]]'s QuickDrop battery swap feature, but the allience's partnership with [[Better Place]] influenced Nissan's distribution plan for the U.S. which was based upon availability of [[electric vehicle network]]s.<ref name="NY Times, Motavalli">{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/08/03/nissan-unveils-leaf-electric-car/|date=2009-08-03
|title=Nissan Unveils Leaf, an Electric Car|author=[http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/author/jim-motavalli/ Jim Motavalli]|accessdate=2009-10-05|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autocar.co.uk/News/NewsArticle/AllCars/242048/|title=Nissan Leaf EV launched|date=2009-09-15|accessdate=2009-10-06|author=Matt Saunders}}</ref>

