;Japan
Nissan announced that the price of the Leaf in Japan starts at {{yen|3.76}} million (approximately {{USD|44,600}}) before any current [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Japan|
tax breaks]].<ref name=GCC0330/><ref name=PriceUS/> The Leaf is eligible for a {{yen|770,000}} government tax credit if current incentives continue through fiscal year 2010, thus reducing the net price to {{yen|2.99}} million ({{USD|35,500}}). The Leaf is also be exempt from the car-weight and car-acquisition taxes.<ref name=GCC0330/>

Nissan offers customers various purchasing methods, including a financing program that allows consumers to pay <U+00A5>2.4 million (US$28,500) and then a monthly fee of <U+00A5>10,000 (US$119), which includes electricity costs.<ref name=GCC0330/> Other services that are available include charging equipment arranged by Nissan dealers who provide assistance to customers in the installation of charging facilities in their homes. Nissan committed to install 200-volt regular chargers at 2,200 Nissan dealers nationwide before December 2010; about 200 dealers would also have quick-charging facilities that provide 80% of battery capacity in less than 30&nbsp;minutes. Nissan guarantees the availability of at least one quick-charge unit within a 40-kilometer radius throughout the country.<ref name=GCC0330/><ref name=QuickCharger/> The 220&nbsp;V quick charger went on sale on May 2010 for <U+00A5>1,470,000 (around US$17,450) excluding taxes and installation. The quick chargers were developed by Nissan but they also work with electric cars from other automakers. Nissan offers variants built for hot and cold climate for <U+00A5>1,732,500 and <U+00A5>1,543,500 respectively.<ref name=QuickCharger/>

The Leaf pre-order process began on April 1 through Nissan dealers across Japan.<ref name=GCC0330/><ref name=GCC0422/> During the first three weeks, individuals accounted for 64% of the pre-orders, and fleet orders represented the remaining 36%. Among individuals, older consumers (age 50 and higher) accounted for 61% of the orders.<ref name=GCC0422>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/04/leaf-japan-20100422.html#more|title=Pre-order of Nissan LEAF in Japan Reaches 3,754 Units in 3 Weeks; 64% from Individuals, Skewing to Older Buyers|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-04-22|accessdate=2010-04-24}}</ref> As of late May 2010, Nissan announced it had already received 6,000 pre-orders,<ref name=NYTSoldOut>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/26/business/26auto.html?hpw|title=Nissan Says Electric Car Is Sold Out for This Year|work=The New York Times|author=Nick Bunkley|date=2010-05-25|accessdate=2010-05-26}}</ref> thus reaching their Japan's sales target for FY2010.<ref name=GCC0422/>
The first Leaf delivery took place at the [[Kanagawa Prefecture]] on December 22, 2010. Ten units were delivered to the Kanagawa Prefecture Government, which decided to assign six Leafs for official use and the other four will be available for the [[car rental]] service run by the local government.<ref name=JapanDeliver1/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/articles/94510/20101222/nissan-leaf-japan-kanagawa-prefectural-government.htm|title=Nissan delivers first LEAF cars in Japan|work=International Business Times|date=2010-12-22|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref>

;China
Nissan plans to release the Leaf in limited quantities to government customers in China in 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/businessNews/idINIndia-47546620100408?pageNumber=1&virtualBrandChannel=0|title=
Nissan to sell Leaf in China in 2011|publisher=Reuters|date=2010-04-08|accessdate=2010-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan-global.com/EN/NEWS/2010/_STORY/100423-01-e.html|title=Nissan March and NV200 Featured at 2010 Beijing International Automobile Exhibition - All-electric Nissan LEAF among Nissan lineup on display|publisher=[[Nissan]]|date=2010-04-23|accessdate=2010-04-24}}</ref>

===Australasia===
Leaf sales in Australia are scheduled for 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.drive.com.au/drive/motor-news/nissans-affordable-electric-car-20100315-q8m8.html|title=Nissan<U+2019>s <U+201C>affordable<U+201D> electric car|date=2010-03-15|publisher=Drive|author=Matt Campbell|accessdate=2010-04-10}}</ref>

===Europe===
On July 2010 Nissan announced the final Leaf pricing for the first four European countries where the electric vehicle will be launched in early 2011.<ref name=Nissan073010/> European prices, including the cost of the battery, are almost {{<U+20AC>|10,000}} more expensive than the US price.<ref name=JustAuto0510>{{cite web|url=http://www.just-auto.com/news/nissan-leaf-costlier-in-europe-even-with-incentives_id104404.aspx?lk=dm|publisher=Just-Auto|title=UK: Nissan Leaf costlier in Europe even with incentives|author=Graeme Roberts|date=2010-05-17|accessdate=2010-05-17}}</ref> Most countries, except the Netherlands, have [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Europe|government incentives]] in the point of sale. Nissan also said that "''the Leaf would allow owners to save <U+20AC>600 a year in fuel costs compared with an equivalent internal combustion model.''"<ref name=JustAuto0510/>  Nissan explained that its decision to launch in the selected four countries first is due to the existing government incentives for electric cars and the ongoing efforts to deploy [[charging station|charging infrastructure]]. The carmaker announced that the Leaf will be available in the other major [[Western Europe]]an countries by late 2011.<ref name=ABGreen0510/> According to Nissan, 12,000 European customers signed up to receive regular updates, and the company began taking orders in Portugal and Ireland on July 30, 2010. The process started in the U.K. in September 2010.<ref name=Nissan073010/>

[[File:Nissan Leaf 004.JPG|thumb|Rear view of the Nissan Leaf exhibited at the 2009 [[Tokyo Motor Show]]]]

;Ireland
The Leaf will be launched in Ireland in February 2011 at a price of {{<U+20AC>|29,995}} after a {{<U+20AC>|5,000}} [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Ireland|government incentive]] is applied.<ref name=Nissan073010/><ref name=JustAuto0510/> Buyers will be exempted from the vehicle registration tax.<ref name=ABGreen0510/>

;Netherlands
According to Nissan, the Leaf roll-out in the Netherlands was rescheduled from December 2010 to June 2011 due to the high demand.<ref name=Nissan073010/> The announced price is {{<U+20AC>|32,839}}.<ref name=ABGreen0510/><ref name=NissanNl>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissan.nl/NL/nl/inside-nissan/innovation-and-technology/leaf_prijzen.html|title=Leaf prijzen|language=Dutch|publisher=Nissan Netherlands|accessdate=2010-05-19}}</ref> Existing incentives include total exemption of the registration fee and road taxes, which result in savings of approximately {{<U+20AC>|5,324}} for private car owners over four years<ref name=NissanNl/> and {{<U+20AC>|19,000}} for corporate owners over five years.<ref name=ABGreen0510/> Leaf buyers will also have access to parking spaces in Amsterdam reserved for [[battery electric vehicle]]s. In the city  a car cannot be purchased without the owner having secure a parking space, so Leaf buyers will avoid the current wait for a parking place in Amsterdam, which can reach up to 10 years in some parts of the city.<ref name=JustAuto0510/>

;Portugal
Leaf retail deliveries in Portugal are scheduled for January 2011 at a price of {{<U+20AC>|30,250}} after a {{<U+20AC>|5,000}} [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Portugal|government subsidy]].<ref name=Nissan073010/> Some consumers might benefit from an additional {{<U+20AC>|1,500}} incentive if they turn in their used car as part of the down payment for the new electric car.<ref name=JustAuto0510/><ref name=Portg0510/> As of May 2010 there are only about a dozen [[recharging station]]s in the country, but the government expects to deploy 320 before the end of 2010 and 1,300 by the end of 2011.<ref name=Portg0510>{{cite news|url=http://jn.sapo.pt/blogs/velocidade/archive/2010/05/17/nissan-j-225-divulgou-pre-231-o-do-carro-el-233-ctrico-leaf.aspx|title=Nissan j<U+00E1> divulgou pre<U+00E7>o do carro el<U+00E9>ctrico Leaf|work=Journal de Not<U+00ED>cias|date=2010-05-17|accessdate=2010-05-17|language=Portuguese}}</ref> On December 22, 2010 Nissan delivered at [[Lisbon]] the first nine Leafs to its commercial customer the MOBI.E consortium, and another unit to the Portuguese government as a loan for trial purposes. Deliveries for individual customers will begin in early 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegreencarwebsite.co.uk/blog/index.php/2010/12/23/electric-leaf-makes-european-debut-in-portugal/|title=Electric Leaf makes European debut in Portugal|publisher=The Green Car Website|date=2010-12-23|accessdate=2020-12-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newsroom.nissan-europe.com/uk/en-gb/Media/Media.aspx?mediaid=74417|title=Portuguese Consortium MOBI.E Receives 100% Electric NISSAN LEAF Fleet|date=2010-12-22|publisher=Nissan Europe|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref>

;United Kingdom

The Leaf will go on sale in the United Kingdom in March 2011 at a price of {{GBP|23,990}} including the new 20% [[VAT]] and after discounting the [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#United Kingdom|Plug-in Car Grant]] of {{GBP|5,000}} that came into effect in January 2011.<ref name=Nissan073010/><ref name=Times7129202/> Despite the government incentive, the Leaf price still will be around {{GBP|4,000}} more expensive than the price of a basic [[Toyota Prius]].<ref name=Times7129202>{{cite news|url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/engineering/article7129202.ece|title=Nissan prices electric car at <U+00A3>23,350|work=The Times|date=2010-05-18|accessdate=2010-05-18 | location=London | first=Robert | last=Lea}}</ref>

===North America===
;United States

The Leaf has two trim levels available, the SV and the SL. The SV trim level includes an advanced [[navigation system]] and [[Internet]]/[[smart phone]] connectivity to the vehicle. The SL trim level adds several convenience features, including rearview monitor, fast charge receptacle, solar panel spoiler, fog lights, and automatic headlights for an additional {{USD|940}}. Leaf customers have the option to buy a [[charging station|home charging station]] through Nissan at cost of around {{USD|2,200}} including installation, which was eligible for a 50% federal tax credit up to {{USD|2,000}} until December 31, 2010,<ref name=PriceUS/><ref name=GreenAuto0330/> and afterwards the credit was reduced to 30% up to {{USD|1,000}} for individuals and {{USD|30,000}} for commercial buyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plugincars.com/breaking-electric-car-charging-station-tax-credit-extended-lower-30-pre-stimulus-levels-106580.html|title=Electric Car Charging Station Tax Credit Extended, But at Lower 30% Pre-Stimulus Levels|publisher=PluginCars.com|date=2010-12-17|accessdate=2020-12-23}}</ref> The charging stations operate on a 240-volt supply and are built and installed by [[AeroVironment]]. This one-stop-shop process includes a home assessment by a certified technician to ensure that the buyer's garage is plug-in ready.<ref name=GreenAuto0330/>
[[File:Three LEAFs charging California.jpg|thumb|left|Nissan Leafs recharging]]

Nissan's base [[suggested retail price|retail price]] in the US is {{USD|32,780}} before any applicable [[tax incentive]]s (federal [[tax credit]]).<ref name=PriceUS/><ref name=GreenAuto0330/> Nissan also has 36 month lease option for {{USD|349}} a month for the SV trim and {{USD|379}} a month for the SL trim, plus an initial payment of {{USD|1,999}} in both cases.<ref name=LeafUSPrice>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/tags/show/price#/leaf-electric-car/feature/pricing_information|title=Nissan Leaf Price: Packages and features|publisher=Nissan (Leaf US website)|accessdate=2010-12-23}}</ref> Considering the {{USD|7,500}} [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#United States|electric vehicle federal tax credit]] established by the [[American Clean Energy and Security Act]] of 2009, the net price can drop to {{USD|25,280}} for eligible customers, depending on exact tax circumstances. The federal tax credit shrinks by automaker after it has sold at least 200,000 vehicles in the U.S., and then it phases out over a year.<ref name=PriceUS/> Nissan explained that it priced the Leaf lower in the US than in Japan because it wants to achieve higher sales in that market.<ref name=PriceUS/>

Other [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Other states|state and local incentives]] are available and may further decrease the cost. California has a {{USD|5,000}} statewide rebate; [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] has a {{USD|5,000}} tax credit, and [[Oregon]] has a {{USD|1,500}} tax credit.<ref name=GreenAuto0330>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/03/30/2011-nissan-leaf-us-pricing-officially-announced-as-low-as-25/ |title=2011 Nissan Leaf US pricing officially announced: as low as $25,280* |publisher=GreenAutoBlog|date=2010-03-30|accessdate=2010-03-30}}</ref> However, in California, according to ''[[The New York Times]]'', the {{USD|4.1}}&nbsp;million allocated for the program in 2010  might be exhausted in a few months, as the rebates are provided on a first-come, first-served basis; the program will exhaust the funds available after only 820 car owners have benefited, assuming an average {{USD|5,000}} rebate. As a result, the benefit might not be available by late 2010, when the Leaf is scheduled to be launched. According to staff from the California Center for Sustainable Energy, which is in charge of the program, additional funding will be allocated in 2011 in a similar order of magnitude as the funds allocated for 2010.<ref name=NYT0310>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/03/19/californias-new-5000-e-v-rebates-grab-em-fast/?emc=eta1|title=California<U+2019>s New $5,000 E.V. Rebates: Grab <U+2018>Em Fast|author=Jim Motavalli|work=The New York Times|date=2010-03-19|accessdate=2010-06-10}}</ref>

[[File:Nissan Leaf EPA fuel economy label.jpg|thumb|The [[Monroney label]] shows [[EPA]]'s combined  city/highway [[fuel economy in automobiles|fuel economy]] rating of 99 [[miles per gallon gasoline equivalent]] for the 2011 Nissan Leaf.<ref name=NYTEPA/>]]

Following the announcement by General Motors that they were anticipating their [[Chevrolet Volt]] model to achieve a city fuel economy figure of {{convert|230|mpgUS|abbr=on}} plus 25&nbsp;[[kWh]]/100&nbsp;mi (85[[mpgge|mpg<sub>ge</sub>]] combined), Nissan announced on August 11, 2009, via its "NissanEVs" [[Twitter]] account,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2009/08/11/nissan-pokes-fun-at-the-volt-claims-367-mpg-equivalent-for-leaf/|title=Nissan pokes fun at Volt, claims 367 mpg equivalent for Leaf EV|date=2009-08-11|author=[http://www.autoblog.com/bloggers/alex-nunez/ Alex Nunez]|accessdate=2009-10-05|publisher=AutoBlog.com}}</ref> that they anticipated the Leaf to reach {{convert|367|mpgUS|abbr=on}} using the [[U.S. Department of Energy|Department of Energy]]'s formula<ref name="petroleum-equivalency">{{cite journal| author = [[United States Department of Energy|U.S. Department of Energy (DOE)]], Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy| title = 10 CFR Part 474, Electric and Hybrid Vehicle Research, Development, and Demonstration Program; Petroleum-Equivalent Fuel Economy Calculation; Final Rule| publisher = [[United States Government Printing Office|U.S. GPO]], Federal Register Vol. 64 No. 113| date=2000-07-12| url = http://frwebgate.access.gpo.gov/cgi-bin/getdoc.cgi?dbname=2000_register&docid=00-14446-filed.pdf| format = PDF| accessdate = 2006-09-22}}</ref> plus 22.5&nbsp;kWh/100&nbsp;miles (150[[mpgge|mpg<sub>ge</sub>]] combined).<ref name="EPA DOT proposed rulemaking">{{cite journal|url=http://www.epa.gov/oms/climate/regulations/420r10012a.pdf|title=Proposed Rulemaking to Establish Light-Duty Vehicle Greenhouse Gas Emission Standards and Corporate Average Fuel Economy Standards|publisher=[[EPA]]|accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref>

According to Nissan, the Leaf expected [[all-electric range]] is {{convert|100|mi|disp=flip}} on the EPA city driving cycle and remains the same as the EV-11 prototype.<ref name='leaf_specs'>{{cite web| url=http://www.nissan-zeroemission.com/EN/LEAF/specs.html| publisher=Nissan| title=Nissan LEAF Specs| accessdate=2009-08-03}}</ref> However, the United States Environmental Protection Agency official range is {{Convert|73|mi|disp=flip}} based on the five-cycle tests using varying driving conditions and climate controls.<ref name=NYTEPA/><ref name=GCCEPA>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/11/leaf-20101122.html#more|title=US EPA rates Nissan LEAF fuel economy as 99 mpg-equivalent (combined); 73-mile range|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-11-22|accessdate=2010-11-23}}</ref> The [[Federal Trade Commission]], which is supposed to label all [[alternative-fuel vehicle]]s, disagrees with the EPA rating, and considers that the correct range is between {{Convert|96|to|110|mi}}. Although the FTC does not conduct its own tests as EPA does, it relies on a standard set by [[SAE International]] and the results reported by automakers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/11/24/the-case-of-the-nissan-leafs-unexpected-sticker/?ref=automobiles|title=The Case of the Nissan Leaf<U+2019>s Unexpected Sticker|author=Matthew L. Wald|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-11-24|accessdate=2010-11-25}}</ref> Based on third-party test drives carried out in the US, reviewers have found that the range available from a single charge can vary up to 40% in real-world situations; reports vary from about {{convert|62|mi|disp=flip}} to almost {{convert|138|mi|disp=flip}} depending on driving style, load, traffic conditions, weather (i.e. wind, atmospheric density), and accessory use.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/16/driving-the-nissan-leaf-electric-car-reveals-range-variability/|title=Driving the Nissan Leaf Electric Car Reveals Range Variability|author=Jerry Garrett|work=The New York Times|date=2010-07-16|accessdate=2010-07-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://reviews.cnet.com/8301-13746_7-20008319-48.html |title=Nissan Leaf has 100-mile range--give or take 40 percent |date=2010-06-21 |author= |publisher=CNET |accessdate=2010-06-26 }}</ref> Nissan tested the Leaf under several scenarios to estimate real-world range figures, obtaining a worst case scenario of {{Convert|47|mi|disp=flip}} and a best case scenario of {{Convert|138|mi|disp=flip}}. The following table summarizes the results under each scenario tested using EPA's L4 test cycle:<ref name=ForbesRange>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.forbes.com/energysource/2010/06/11/warning-your-mileage-may-vary/|title=Electric Car Warning: Actual Mileage May Vary|work=[[Forbes]]|author=Joann Muler|date=2010-06-11|accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref><ref name=ABGRange>{{cite web|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2010/06/14/nissan-pegs-leaf-range-between-47-and-138-miles-individual-resu/|title=Nissan pegs Leaf range between 47 and 138 miles, individual results may vary|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|author= Eric Loveday|date=2010-06-14|accessdate=2010-10-21}}</ref>

