In October 2009 Nissan announced the Zero Emission Tour, with stops in 22 North American cities.<ref name=nissanustour>{{cite web|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/nissan-announces-dates-for-nissan-leaf-zero-emission-tour-65605762.html|title=Nissan Announces Dates For Nissan LEAF Zero Emission Tour|publisher=PR Newswire|author=Nissan|date=2010-10-22|accessdate=2010-12-21}}</ref> At each stop on the tour, visitors were able to view the car and learn about the benefits of zero-emission driving. The first stop of the tour was in [[Los Angeles]] on November 13, 2009, marking the unveiling of the LEAF in North America.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-nissan-leaf14-2009nov14,0,6555931.story|title= Nissan is turning over a new zero-emission Leaf|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2009-11-14|accessdate=2009-11-20 | first=Tiffany | last=Hsu}}</ref> Other stops on the tour included [[San Francisco]]; [[Seattle]]; [[Vancouver]]; [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]; [[Houston]]; [[Washington, D.C.]]; and [[Orlando, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wot.motortrend.com/nissan-leaf-zero-emission-tour-rolling-through-22-north-american-cities-5738.html|title=Nissan Leaf Zero Emission Tour Rolling Through 22 North American Cities|work=Motor Trend Magazine|date=2009-10-23|accessdate=2010-12-31}}</ref> The tour ended in February 2010 in [[New York City]] after visiting 24 cities, including two ([[Atlanta]] and [[Boston]]) that were added to the original itinerary due to requests. Nissan estimates that 100,000 people saw the company<U+2019>s lithium-ion battery car.<ref name=NYT022009>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/02/12/nissan-leaf-electric-car-comes-to-new-york/?scp=1&sq=Nissan%20Leaf&st=cse|title=Nissan Leaf Electric Car Comes to New York|author=Jim Motavalli|work=The New York Times|date=2010-02-12|accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref><ref name=Electric>{{cite web|url=http://electricnick.com/2010/02/12/nissan-leaf-tour-ends-nyc/|title=Nissan Leaf Tour Ends In NYC With Success |publisher=Electricnick.com |date=2010-02-12|accessdate=2010-02-13}}</ref>

Nissan conducted a [[test drive]] tour<U+2014>dubbed the Drive Electric Tour<U+2014>in several cities in the initial U.S. launch markets. The tour began on October 1, 2010, at the AltCar Expo in Santa Monica, California, and continued in Anaheim, San Diego, Los Angeles, and San Jose. In November, the tour moved to Hillsboro, Oregon; Seattle, Washington; and San Francisco. The following month the tour continued in [[Tucson]] and Tempe, Arizona; and Austin, Texas. The cities to be visited in 2011 will be announced later, but the promotional tour is expected to end by March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoblog.com/2010/09/08/nissan-releases-u-s-tour-dates-for-leaf-schedule-your-drive-ti/|title=Nissan releases U.S. tour dates for Leaf; schedule your drive time now|publisher=[[Autoblog]]|date=2010-09-08|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nissanusa.com/leaf-electric-car/events/index#/leaf-electric-car/events/index|title=Events: drive electric tour, sponsored by the 100% electric Nissan LEAF|publisher=[[Nissan]] USA|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref>

Nissan began the online-only reservation process on April 20, 2010, charging a fully refundable {{USD|99}} reservation fee that allowed customers to secure a place on the list to purchase or lease a Leaf. It limited reservations to one per household<ref name=Leaf0420/><ref name=NYT0420/><ref name=GCC0410>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/04/leaf-20100419.html#more|title=Nissan to Begin Taking LEAF Reservations on 20 April; 115,00 Registrants Have First Priority|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-04-19|accessdate=2010-04-19}}</ref> and by July 2010 it had received approximately 17,000 reservations.<ref name=GCC072810/>  It reported that about 75% of U.S. reservations were for the premium model SL trim, and more than 55% of the reservations were from its primary launch markets in California, Washington, Oregon, Arizona, and Tennessee.<ref name=GCC072810/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/04/nissan-says-6600-us-consumers-have-already-reserved-a-leaf-electric-vehicle.html|title=Nissan Says 6,600 U.S. Consumers Have Already Reserved a Leaf Electric Vehicle|author=Scott Doggett |publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|date=2010-04-24|accessdate=2010-04-27}}</ref> By September 2010 Nissan announced that it had reached 20,000 reservations, and it did not accept any more reservations for the remainder of 2010.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/09/24/thinking-of-buying-a-nissan-leaf-get-in-line/|title=Thinking of Buying a Nissan Leaf? Get in Line|author=Stephen Williams|work=The New York Times|date=2010-09-24|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref>

[[File:Nissan Leaf Drive Electric Tour Black 2010.jpg|thumb|Nissan Leaf used for test drives at the Drive Electric Tour opening in [[Santa Monica, California]]]]

Firm orders started in August, and deliveries began in select markets and limited quantities in December 2010, with more availability scheduled for 2011, and full U.S. market rollout in 2012.<ref name=Leaf0420/><ref name=NYT0420/><ref name=GCC072810/> Nissan is initially limiting Leaf sales to California, Washington, Oregon, Arizona, and Tennessee. These areas were selected because they are home to the [[EV Project]], which was awarded a grant from the [[United States Department of Energy]] and is the largest electric vehicle and infrastructure deployment in the US.<ref name=GCC072810>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencarcongress.com/2010/07/leaf-20100728.html#more|title=Nissan<U+2019>s US Roll-Out Plan for the LEAF|publisher=[[Green Car Congress]]|date=2010-07-28|accessdate=2010-07-28}}</ref><ref name=CD72810>{{cite web|url=http://blog.caranddriver.com/nissan-leaf-batteries-to-carry-8-year100000-mile-warranty-launch-markets-announced/?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed:+caranddriver/blog+(Car+and+Driver+Blog)&utm_content=Google+Reader|title=Nissan Leaf Batteries to Carry 8-Year/100,000-Mile Warranty, Launch Markets  Announced|work=[[Car and Driver]]|date=2010-07-28|accessdate=2010-07-28}}</ref> The second roll-out is scheduled to follow in January 2011 and will include Texas and Hawaii. In April 2011, the Leaf will be launched in North Carolina, Florida, Georgia, Washington DC, Virginia, Maryland, South Carolina and Alabama. The roll-out to the rest of the US will begin in the third quarter of 2011 with nationwide availability by the end of 2011.<ref name=GCC072810/>

The first Leaf customer delivery took place in a Nissan dealership in [[Petaluma, California]] on December 11, 2010, and it was followed by a commemoration event at [[San Francisco City Hall]] Plaza. Nissan explained that the first delivery went to the first person in the United States to place a Nissan Leaf on-line order.<ref name=LaunchUS/><ref name=LaunchUS2>{{cite news|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/12/11/BALT1GPFFC.DTL&tsp=1|title=Redwood city man gets first Nissan Leaf|author=Nanette Asimov|work=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2010-12-11|accessdate=2010-12-11}}</ref> During the following days similar first delivery events took place in [[San Diego, California]]; [[Arizona]]; [[Oregon]]; and [[Washington (U.S. state)|Washington]], and [[Tennessee]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/2010/dec/13/nissan-turns-over-a-new-leaf-to-its-owner/|title=Nissan turns over a new Leaf ... to its new owner|publisher=Sign On San Diego|author=Onell R. Soto|date=2010-12-13|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/nissan-delivers-seattles-first-100-electric-nissan-leaf-112091874.html|title=Nissan Delivers Seattle's First 100% Electric Nissan LEAF|publisher=PR Newswire|author=Nissan|date=2010-12-17|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> The first Leaf was delivered in [[Nashville, Tennessee]] on December 21, 2010, completing the first delivery in each of the first launch markets.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-14/nissan-s-first-electric-leaf-in-tenn-on-dec-21.html|title=Nissan's first electric Leaf in Tenn. on Dec. 21|work=Bloomberg|date=2010-12-14|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref>

[[File:First Customer owned Nissan Leaf.jpg|thumb|First Nissan Leaf delivered in the U.S. on the road south of [[San Francisco]]]]

The Nissan Leaf will also be available through two [[car rental]] companies and [[carsharing]] services in selected markets.<ref name=LATimes080910>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-travel-briefcase-20100809,0,7868968.story|title=Car rental companies to offer electric Nissan Leafs|author=Hugo Mart<U+00ED>n|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=2010-08-09|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref><ref name=Hertz>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/12/hertz-plugs-into-the-nissan-leaf/|title=Hertz Plugs Into the Nissan Leaf|author=Jim Motavalli|work=The New York Times|date=2010-05-12|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> [[Enterprise Rent-A-Car]] initially plans to offer about 500 vehicles at dealerships in Los Angeles, San Diego, Portland, and Seattle beginning in January 2011.<ref name=LATimes080910/><ref name=Enterprise>{{cite news|url=http://www.autorentalnews.com/News/Story/2010/07/Enterprise-Rent-A-Car-to-Begin-Offering-Electric-Vehicles-in-U-S.aspx|title=Enterprise Rent-A-Car to Begin Offering Electric Vehicles in U.S.|publisher=Auto Rental News|date=2010-07-28|accessdate=2010-08-09}}</ref> [[Hertz Rent-a-Car]] plans to offer the Leaf and other [[electric car]]s at select locations in the U.S. and Europe, including New York City; Washington, D.C.; and San Francisco in 2011.<ref name=NYT1207>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/07/hertz-puts-electric-cars-on-the-fast-track-starting-in-new-york/|title=Hertz Puts Electric Cars on the Fast Track, Starting in New York
|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Jim Motavalli|date=2010-12-07|accessdate=2010-12-08}}</ref> The Leaf will also be available at some [[Connect by Hertz]] carsharing locations, a service with operations in London, Paris, Madrid, Berlin, and 150 locations in the United States.<ref name=Hertz/> The carsharing rental by the hour of the Leaf is scheduled to begin in [[New York City]] on December 15, 2010.<ref name=NYT1207/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.plugincars.com/hertz-details-hourly-electric-car-rentals-including-nissan-chevy-mitsubishi-tesla-smart-and-coda-106|title=Hertz Details Hourly Electric Car Rentals Including Nissan, Chevy, Mitsubishi, Tesla, Smart, and Coda|publisher=PluginCars.com|date=2010-12-06|accessdate=2010-12-08}}</ref>

On July 27, 2010, Nissan announced that the Leaf's battery warranty is for eight years or {{convert|100000|mi|disp=flip}}.<ref name="GCC072710"/><ref name="CNN072710"/> On July 16, 2010, Nissan conducted an e-mail survey among the 16,000 individuals that made a reservation in the U.S. and a sample of other potential customers regarding the terms of the [[battery pack]] guarantee. The survey was sent two days after General Motors announced that the Chevrolet Volt's battery was guaranteed for eight years or {{convert|100000|mi|disp=flip}}.<ref name=NYTsurvey>{{cite news|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/21/nissan-questions-consumers-about-leaf-battery-warranty/|title=Nissan Questions Consumers About Leaf Battery Warranty|author=Jim Motavalli|work=The New York Times|date=2010-07-21|accessdate=2010-07-25}}</ref><ref name=EdmundsSurvey>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.edmunds.com/greencaradvisor/2010/07/nissan-seeking-customer-input-on-leaf-battery-warranty-is-60000-miles-enough.html|title=Nissan Seeking Customer Input on Leaf Battery Warranty: Is 60,000 Miles Enough? |author=John O'Dell|publisher=[[Edmunds.com]]|date=2010-07-22|accessdate=2010-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/business/15auto.html?_r=1&ref=automobiles|title=G.M. to Offer 8-Year Guarantee for New Electric Car<U+2019>s Battery|author=Tom Zeller Jr.|work=The New York Times|date=2010-07-14|accessdate=2010-07-25}}</ref> The multiple-choice survey had a batch of battery warranty related questions focused on the responder's preference between a five-year or {{convert|60000|mi|adj=on|disp=flip}} warranty or an eight-year or {{convert|100000|mi|adj=on|disp=flip}} warranty.<ref name=NYTsurvey/><ref name=EdmundsSurvey/> A Nissan spokeswoman commented that the company wanted to hear from future Leaf drivers to ensure Nissan is meeting the expectations of the marketplace before deciding its warranty policy.<ref name=NYTsurvey/><ref name=EdmundsSurvey/>

;Canada
The Leaf will go on sale in Canada in January 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.windsorstar.com/technology/LEAF+will+sale+Japan/3725447/story.html#ixzz13T3O5CxB|title=LEAF will go on sale in U.S., Japan|work=[[Windsor Star]]|date=2010-10-26|accessdate=2010-11-26}}</ref> [[Ontario]] residents are eligible for a [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Canada|rebate]] of {{CAD|8,500}}. The rebate is available for purchasing or leasing a [[plug-in electric vehicle]]s to the first 10,000 applicants who qualify.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nissan.ca/vehicles/ms/leaf/en/news-expanded2.aspx?item=1|publisher=Nissan Canada|title=Nissan LEAF Eligible for $8,500 Incentive in Ontario|accessdate=2010-11-26}}</ref><ref name=Ontario10>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.ontario.ca/mto/en/2010/06/ontario-paves-the-way-for-electric-vehicles.html|title=Ontario Paves The Way For Electric Vehicles|publisher=Newsroom Ontario|date=2010-06-18|accessdate=2010-06-21}}</ref> [[Communauto]], the oldest carsharing service in North America, will add 50 Nissan Leaf to its fleet in [[Quebec]] when the vehicle becomes available to the Canadian market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nissan.ca/vehicles/ms/leaf/en/news-expanded2.aspx?item=3|title=Communauto to offer all-electric Nissan LEAF to clients in 2011|publisher=Nissan Canada|accessdate=2010-11-26}}</ref>

;Mexico
In October 2009, Nissan announced that it had reached an agreement with the local government of Mexico City, by which 500 units of the Leaf will be delivered by 2011 for use of government and corporate fleets. In exchange, [[charging station|recharging infrastructure]] will be deployed by the city government, and an exemption from the ownership tax is being pursued.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nissan alista puntos de recarga del Leaf|url=http://www.cnnexpansion.com/negocios/2010/06/02/nissan-alista-puntos-de-recarga-del-leaf|publisher=CNN Expansion|date=2010-06-02|accessdate=2010-09-26|language=Spanish}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nissan aims to bring electric car to Mexico City in 2011|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/nissan-aims-to-bring-electric-car-to-mexico-city-in-2011-2009-10-28|publisher=Market Watch|date=2009-10-28|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> This agreement will allow Mexico to become the first Latin American market where the Leaf will be available.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nissan Leaf heading south of the border to Mexico City |date=2009-11-03|url=http://green.autoblog.com/2009/11/03/nissan-leaf-heading-south-of-the-border-to-mexico-city//
|publisher=[[AutoblogGreen]]|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> The Leaf will be available for the general public starting in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nissan llevar<U+00E1> 500 unidades del Leaf a M<U+00E9>xico en 2011 |url=http://es.autoblog.com/2009/10/29/nissan-llevara-500-unidades-del-leaf-a-mexico-en-2011/|publisher=Auto Blog en Espa<U+00F1>ol|accessdate=2010-09-26|language=Spanish}}</ref>

==Reception==
Since the initial series of announcements in 2009, a former [[Tesla Motors]] marketing manager criticized Nissan about the cooling system chosen for thermal management in [[lithium-ion battery]] packs,<ref name=Wired/> which may be a factor to the long-term performance of the battery. There may also be an overestimation of the announced {{convert|100|mi|km|adj=on|disp=flip}} range that was computed using LA-4 or "city" mode, which may underestimate the energy draw during highway driving conditions.<ref name=Wired>{{cite web|url=http://www.wired.com/autopia/2010/01/nissan-leaf-2/|title=In Race to Market, Nissan<U+2019>s Electric Car Takes Shortcuts|publisher=[[Wired (magazine)]]|author= Darryl Siry|date=2010-01-22|accessdate=2010-03-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetruthaboutcars.com/ev-range-high-anxiety-normal-driving-may-cut-range-in-half/|title=EV Range High Anxiety: Normal Driving May Cut Range In Half|publisher=The Truth About Cars|author=Paul Niedermeyer|date=2009-12-18|accessdate=2010-03-20}}</ref>

[[File:Nissan Leaf WAS 2010 8902.JPG|thumb|Nissan Leaf with [[Level 1, 2, and 3 charging|Level 2]] [[recharging station|recharging station unit]] displayed at the 2010 [[Washington Auto Show]]]]

The American magazine ''[[Consumer Reports]]'' noted that while charger costs vary between {{USD|700}} and {{USD|1,200}}, an at-home charger and its installation cost more than {{USD|2,000}} even for simple installations.<ref name=ConsumerR/> Nissan estimates a typical charger installation costs {{USD|2,200}}. The article did not mention that home charger installations are eligible for a 50% [[Government incentives for plug-in electric vehicles#Charging Equipment|federal tax credit]] up to {{USD|2,000}}.<ref name=HC0310>{{cite web|url=http://www.hybridcars.com/incentives-laws/us-tax-incentives-plug-hybrids-and-electric-cars.html|title=US Tax Incentives for Plug-in Hybrids and Electric Cars|publisher=HybridCars.com|date=2010-03-08|accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref> Consumer Reports noted that the first 5,700 Leaf buyers will get free chargers with federal support in 13 cities. The consumer group also reminded that many older houses with only a 60<U+2013>100&nbsp;amp supply may need a panel upgrade to install a 240-volt circuit, which can cost several thousand dollars.<ref name=ConsumerR>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.consumerreports.org/cars/2010/09/nissan-leaf-electric-car-charger-installation-cost-proves-shocking.html|title=Nissan Leaf electric-car charger installation cost proves shocking|work=[[Consumer Reports]]|date=2010-09-03|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> The additional 220<U+2013>240-volt charger is only required for countries (mainly the North / South American continent) that do not have a 220<U+2013>240-volt [[Mains electricity|domestic grid]] or want faster charging than under 110<U+2013>120-volt.

''Consumer Reports'' also called buyers' attention to the fact that the Leaf's total out-of-pocket costs include a {{USD|595}} acquisition fee and a {{USD|395}} disposition fee. The consumer group also emphasized that the announced lease price of {{USD|349}}-a-month applies only to buyers with good credit (Tier 1, or a [[FICO score]] of 700 or above); for those with less than optimum credit, the monthly rate would increase. They reminded buyers that the lease comes with a 23,000&nbsp;km/year (15,000-mile-per-year) allowance, but additional miles will cost extra.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.consumerreports.org/cars/2010/09/nissan-leaf-lease-details-revealed.html|title=Nissan Leaf lease details revealed|work=[[Consumer Reports]]|date=2010-09-03|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref>

The Leaf has been awarded by multiple organizations. Notable awards include the inclusion by [[Time (magazine)|Time]] magazine as one of the 50 best inventions of 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1934027_1934003_1933970,00.html|title=The 50 Best Inventions of 2009|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time Magazine]]|accessdate=2009-11-13 | date=2009-11-12}}</ref> At the 2010 [[Washington Auto Show]], the Leaf was given the 2010 [[Green Car Vision Award]] by the [[Green Car Journal]] (GCJ), who noted that the Leaf "will provide the features, the styling, and the driving experience that will meet the needs of a sophisticated and demanding market, while producing zero localized emissions and requiring no petroleum fuels."<ref name=GreenAward>{{cite web|url=http://www.greencar.com/articles/nissan-leaf-electric-car-wins-2010-green-car-vision-award.php|publisher=[[Green Car Journal]]|title=Nissan Leaf Electric Car Wins 2010 Green Car Vision Award|author=Green Car Journal Editors| date=2010-01-26|accessdate=2010-01-27}}</ref> ''[[Popular Mechanics]]'', upon awarding the Leaf its 2010 Breakthrough Award, explained that the Nissan Leaf is "not the first pure EV, but [...] hits the mainstream like none of its predecessors." ''Popular Mechanics'' also alluded to the Leaf's {{convert|100|mi|km|disp=flip}} range, which is said to be "enough for most commuters for the price of an average vehicle <U+2013> and with a much lower operating cost than gasoline-powered vehicles."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finance.yahoo.com/news/Nissan-LEAF-Receives-Popular-prnews-2607695599.html?x=0&.v=1|title=Nissan LEAF Receives Popular Mechanics Breakthrough Award|publisher=[[Yahoo]] Finance|date=2010-10-05|accessdate=2010-10-05}}</ref> Other awards received by the Leaf include the 2011 [[European Car of the Year]],<ref name=ECOTY>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/news/8167962/Nissan-Leaf-wins-Car-of-the-Year.html|title=Nissan Leaf wins Car of the Year |accessdate=2010-11-29|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]}}</ref> and being voted one of the three finalists for the 2011 [[North American Car of the Year]] award, to be announced at the 2011 [[North American International Auto Show]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/16/north-american-car-of-the-year-finalists-are-announced/?hpw|title=North American Car of the Year Finalists Are Announced|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=2010-12-16|accessdate=2010-12-16}}</ref>

